\cf2 Taal:\cf3  \cf4 A rhythmic cycle defined by a fixed number of beats. Example: Teentaal consists of 16 beats.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Matra:\cf5  A single beat, serving as the unit to measure the duration of a taal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Avartan: \cf4 One complete cycle of a taal.\
\
\cf2 Sam:\cf4  The first beat of a taal, often emphasized as the starting point for compositions.\
\
\cf2 Vibhag:\cf4  Sections or divisions of a taal. Example: Teentaal has 4 vibhags.\
\
\cf2 Tali: \cf4 A clap used to indicate an accented beat in a taal.\
\
\cf2 Khali: \cf4 An empty or unaccented beat within a taal, providing contrast to the tali.\
\
\cf2 Tabla: \cf4 A pair of hand-played percussion drums frequently used as accompaniment in Kathak performances.\
\
\cf2 Bol: \cf4 A syllable or sound used to represent a specific stroke on the tabla or a rhythmic idea.\
\
\cf2 Theka: \cf4 The specific pattern of bols played on the tabla to establish a taal. Example: Teentaal theka is as below. \
\
DHA DHIN DHIN DHA\
DHA DHIN DHIN DHA\
DHA TIN TIN TA\
TA DHIN DHIN DHA\
\
\cf2 Laya: \cf4 The tempo or speed of a composition, classified as Vilambit (slow), Madhya (medium), and Drut (fast).\
\
\cf2 Tatkar: \cf4 Basic footwork and foundation of Kathak, where rhythmic syllables are produced through stamping in accordance with the taal.\
\
\cf2 Parhant: \cf4 The recitation of bols that correspond to the beats of a composition, often used for practice or teaching.\
\
\cf2 Tora: \cf4 A sequence of bols or syllables that begins and ends on the sam.\
\
\cf2 Tukra: \cf4 A short composition completed within 1 to 3 avartans.\
\
\cf2 Tihai:\cf4  A rhythmic pattern repeated three times, often concluding on the sam.\
\
\cf2 Lari: \cf4 A chain of footwork patterns that typically ends with a tihai.\
\
\cf2 Chakkar / Pheri / Bhramari : \cf4 It refers to controlled pirouettes/turns executed with balance, rhythm, and grace.\
\
\cf2 Chakradar: \cf4 A structure in which a tihai, toda, or paran is repeated three times.\
\
 \cf2 Amad: \cf4 The formal entrance on stage. A tukra performed to greet the audience with a Namaste is called the amad, usually comprising the bols ta, thei, tat. Usually set in Vilambit Laya. \
\
\cf2 Paran:\cf4  Rhythmic bols or phrases derived from the pakhawaj, performed in sync with the taal, often concluding with a tihai.\
\
\cf2 Gat\cf4  :  Gat is derived from 'gati'  or walk or movements. It is a stylized, graceful movement in Kathak dance that emphasizes a specific gait or posture to depict daily life scenes, characters, or narratives. It is characterized by elegant body postures, subtle facial expressions (abhinaya).\
\
\
\cf2 Bhatkhande Notation\cf4  : It is a systematic method of writing and preserving Indian classical music and dance compositions, developed by Pandit Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande.\
\
In Kathak, Bhatkhande notation is used to record and teach bols, tukras, parans, and gats, helping students understand sam, khali, vibhags, and rhythmic symmetry.\
\
The system uses special symbols for rhythmic cycles, with 'X' representing the sam (first beat), '0' for khaali (empty), and numbers (2, 3, 4) for other taalis (beats).\
\
Example : Teentaal Theka \
\
Dha  Dhin  Dhin  Dha |  Dha  Dhin  Dhin  Dha | \
X                                  2    \
\
Dha  Tin  Tin  Ta |  Ta  Dhin  Dhin  Dha  | |\
0                         3       \
\
