\cf2 What is Kathak?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf4 Kathak is a classical dance form of North India. The term Kathak is derived from the Sanskrit word \'93Katha\'94, meaning story. Performers known as Kathakars were traditional storytellers who narrated mythological tales through expressive movement, music, and rhythm, often performing in temples with deep devotion and spiritual fervor. Their storytelling through dance and devotion gradually evolved into the classical form known today as Kathak.\
\
Kathak is broadly divided into Nritta, the pure and technical aspect of dance focusing on rhythm and footwork, and Abhinaya (Natya), the expressive and storytelling aspect that conveys emotions and narratives. Together, these elements allow Kathak to depict life in its entirety, reflecting the three fundamental phases of existence\'97creation, preservation, and destruction.\
\
The dance form is rooted in natural movements and is not restricted to codified hand gestures alone. Its postures are lifelike rather than sculptural, and its abhinaya is characterized by subtlety, grace, and realism. Kathak is also distinguished among Indian classical dances for its frequent and skillful use of pirouettes (chakkars), which form a defining visual and technical feature of the style.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Brief History of Kathak\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \
Kathak originated as a temple-based storytelling tradition in North India, performed by Kathakars who narrated religious and mythological stories through movement and expression. Over time, the dance form transitioned into the royal courts of North India, especially during the Mughal period, where it absorbed Persian influences in music, costume, and aesthetics.\
\
Under royal patronage, Kathak evolved into a sophisticated classical art form, giving rise to distinct gharanas such as Lucknow, Jaipur, Banaras, and Raigarh. Despite historical challenges during the colonial period, Kathak survived and flourished in the modern era through dedicated gurus and performers.\
\
