\cf2 Bhakti Rasa in Kathak\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 Bhakti rasa, the sentiment of devotion, forms the spiritual foundation of Kathak. Rooted in the Vaishnava bhakti tradition, Kathak often portrays divine love and devotion, especially through stories of Lord Krishna and Radha. The dancer expresses surrender, longing, joy, and union with the divine through subtle abhinaya, rhythmic movement, and musical interpretation.\
\
Bhakti rasa in Kathak transcends mere storytelling; it becomes a medium for spiritual experience, connecting the performer and the audience to a deeper sense of devotion and inner reflections.\'a0\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa297\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Kathak Dance Dress, Jewelry, Makeup\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 Kathak costume, jewellery, and makeup together enhance the elegance and expressive quality of the dance. Traditionally, dancers wear flowing costumes such as lehenga-choli (specially for performing Hindu bhakti geeti), and also the anarkali or angarkha which accentuate spins and footwork, while light fabrics allow graceful movement. Jewelry is usually delicate yet striking, including necklaces, earrings, bangles, and sometimes a tikka, complementing the classical aesthetic without overpowering the dancer. Makeup in Kathak is subtle and refined, focusing on expressive eyes with defined liner and brows, natural tones for the face, and a bindi to highlight facial expressions. Overall, the attire and adornments support Kathak\'92s emphasis on grace, clarity, and abhinaya rather than heavy ornamentation.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa297\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Lasya and Tandav in Kathak\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 In Kathak, Tandav and Lasya represent two contrasting yet complementary expressive qualities within the dance form. Tandav reflects vigor, strength, and dynamic energy, and is expressed through powerful footwork, brisk chakkars, sharp movements, and complex rhythmic patterns. It often conveys heroic, masculine, or intense emotional states. Lasya, on the other hand, embodies grace, softness, and fluidity, characterized by gentle movements, subtle transitions, delicate abhinaya, and lyrical expressions. Lasya is commonly associated with themes of love, devotion, and beauty. Together, Tandav and Lasya create balance in Kathak, allowing the dancer to seamlessly shift between strength and softness, rhythm and emotion, forming the complete aesthetic of the dance.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa297\partightenfactor0
\cf2 History of Kathak\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 Kathak originated in the temples of North India, where Kathakars (storytellers) narrated and interpreted tales from Hindu mythology. Over time, these narrations naturally incorporated dance and music, as the Kathakars expressed their devotion in states of spiritual ecstasy. Gradually, this practice evolved into a hereditary and codified art form.\
\
During the Bhakti Movement, Kathak centered primarily on devotional themes associated with Lord Krishna, Radha, and the gopis. These narratives, drawn from sacred texts such as the Bhagavata Purana, symbolized divine love. The relationship between Radha and Krishna came to represent the eternal bond between the Atman (individual soul) and the Paramatma (universal soul)\'97a philosophical concept that Kathak artists conveyed through dance ballets and dramatic presentations.\
\
With the advent of the Mughal period, Kathak entered the royal courts, where it was embraced as a form of aristocratic entertainment while continuing to retain its devotional essence in temple traditions. During this era, Kathak absorbed Persian and Central Asian influences, including elements reminiscent of Sufi whirling, changes in costume from traditional saris and ghagras to the angarkha (Anarkali), and the development of rapid, intricate footwork and swift pirouettes. This period marked a significant phase of stylistic expansion and technical refinement.\
\
A pivotal figure in Kathak\'92s evolution was Nawab Wajid Ali Shah of Lucknow, a distinguished patron, poet, and accomplished dancer. He invited renowned Kathak maestros to his court, institutionalizing the art form and contributing to its formalization and stylistic sophistication. Under his patronage, Kathak attained a heightened level of artistic polish and recognition.\
\
The spread of British colonial rule in the 19th century led to a severe decline of Kathak, along with other Indian classical dance forms. Missionaries and colonial officials disparaged the dance, urging performers to abandon indigenous themes in favor of European and Christian narratives. This criticism was further echoed by sections of Indian society influenced by Victorian moral values, who misunderstood Kathak\'92s spiritual foundation and dismissed it as immoral or regressive.\
\
The Indian independence movement witnessed a resurgence of Kathak, driven by a broader cultural revival and a collective effort to reclaim India\'92s artistic heritage. This revival emerged across both Hindu and Muslim gharanas, with the Lucknow and Jaipur traditions playing a crucial role in restoring Kathak\'92s dignity, structure, and prestige.\
\
Although Kathak is widely regarded as an ancient art form, its present-day practice reflects a process of cultural revival and renewal. Kathak stands unique among Indian classical dances for embodying influences from both Hinduism and Islam. In its modern form, across the major gharanas\'97Lucknow, Jaipur, and Banaras\'97a Kathak performance typically comprises three sections: an invocatory piece (Vandana), a pure dance segment featuring abstract rhythmic compositions such as toda, tukra, tarana, and tihai, and an expressive segment (abhinaya) focused on narrative and emotional expression.\
\
\
