\cf2 Anga Sanyam Shloka\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 Yato Hasta Tato Drishti\
Yato Drishti Tato Manah\
Yato Manah Tato Bhavah\
Yato Bhavah Tato Rasah\
\
Meaning:\
Where the hand goes, the eyes follow.\
Where the eyes go, the mind follows.\
Where the mind goes, emotion arises.\
Where there is emotion, there is aesthetic experience (rasa).\
This shloka explains the fundamental connection between gesture, gaze, mind, emotion, and rasa, forming the philosophical basis of expression (abhinaya) in Kathak and other classical Indian dance forms.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa297\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Guru Vandana \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 Guru Brahma Guru Vishnu\
Guru Devo Maheshwarah\
Guru Sakshat Param Brahma\
Tasmai Shri Gurave Namah\
\
Meaning:\
The Guru is Brahma, the creator.\
The Guru is Vishnu, the preserver.\
The Guru is Maheshwara (Shiva), the destroyer.\
The Guru is verily the Supreme Absolute.\
Salutations to that revered Guru.\
The shloka emphasizes that the Guru shapes the disciple\'92s life completely, creating knowledge, preserving discipline, and destroying ignorance. In the arts, the Guru is the bridge between tradition and the student, guiding not only technique but character, humility, and spiritual growth.\
\
