\cf2 The Nine Rasas (Navarasa)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \
In Kathak, Navarasa refers to the nine primary emotions that a performer expresses through facial expressions (abhinaya), gestures, and body language to convey stories and evoke specific feelings in the audience. Rooted in classical Indian aesthetics, Navarasa is central to the storytelling aspect of Kathak, especially in performances depicting mythological or devotional themes.\
\
\
	Shringara (Love/Attraction) \'96 Romantic or devotional love, often shown in Krishna-Radha pieces.\
Example: Krishna playing the flute and Radha responding with devotion.\
\
	Hasya (Laughter/Comedy) \'96 Joy, humor, or amusement.\
Example: A playful scene of a mischievous Krishna teasing gopis.\
\
	Karuna (Compassion/Sorrow) \'96 Pathos or sadness.\
Example: Sita expressing grief in the Ramayana during her separation from Rama.\
\
	Raudra (Anger) \'96 Fury or wrath.\
Example: Arjuna\'92s battle rage in Mahabharata depictions.\
\
	Veer (Heroism/Courage) \'96 Valor and bravery.\
Example: Bhima fighting demons with determination.\
\
	Bhayanaka (Fear/Terror) \'96 Anxiety or dread.\
Example: Villagers showing fear during the Govardhan Leela, as Krishna lifts the Govardhan hill to protect them from the raging storm sent by Indra.\
\
	Bibhatsa (Disgust/Aversion) \'96 Repulsion or dislike.\
Example: A demon\'92s grotesque actions in mythological stories.\
\
	Adbhuta (Wonder/Amazement) \'96 Awe or surprise.\
Example: A gopi marveling at Krishna\'92s divine miracles.\
\
	Shanta (Peace/Serenity) \'96 Tranquility or calmness.\
Example: Meditative devotion of a yogi or Krishna in serene moments.\
\
In Kathak, a performer may blend these emotions seamlessly during a single piece, using subtle expressions, hand gestures (mudras), and rhythmic movements to convey the story vividly.\
